UPDATE designers SET biography = E'Léo Aerts is a Belgian interior architect and the founder of Alinéa Design Objects, a studio that has spent over four decades distilling the essence of furniture into its purest architectural form. Born in Herentals, a small town near Antwerp, Aerts established his interior design studio in 1983. In 1987, his Meta coffee table became a breakout success for B&B Italia — a collaboration that confirmed his instinct for merging industrial precision with sculptural restraint.\n\n<strong>''The scale, proportions and detailing of a piece are all inspired by understanding how people move through a space, how light falls and how volumes relate to one another.''</strong>\n\nRather than viewing a table or cabinet as a standalone object, Aerts approaches each piece as part of a broader spatial narrative. He swears by soberly designed, functional and timeless creations that can be passed on from generation to generation. Quality, he insists, must always take precedence over quantity. Long before sustainability, cradle-to-cradle and the circular economy entered mainstream discourse, these principles were already embedded in his design philosophy.\n\nIn 1995, the Ziggy vase marked the official launch of Alinéa Design Objects — the label through which Aerts'' designs are promoted and distributed internationally. Ziggy became an enormous commercial success, with more than 15,000 units sold. The UFO serving dish and the Zubazuba champagne cooler followed shortly thereafter, establishing the studio''s ability to move between monumental stone furniture and refined tabletop objects with equal conviction.\n\nhttps://vimeo.com/803009029 | Alinea Design Objects Presents: Angelo M / Furniture Collection\n\nWorking with a small network of local artisans and collaborating closely with Belgian and Italian quarries, Aerts selects his stones for their geological character — ensuring that every table, shelf and object carries the unique signature of its material.\n\nThe Angelo collection, which pairs monolithic natural stone with solid American walnut, has earned international recognition and can be found in residences and galleries far beyond Europe. His Visibile display cabinets, with their architectural glass-and-stone construction, have become another hallmark of the studio.\n\n<strong>''I think of furniture as architectural microstructures — functional, sculptural and attuned to the human experience.''</strong>\n\nhttps://res.cloudinary.com/dif1oamtj/image/upload/w_1200,q_auto:good,f_auto/Screen_Shot_2026-02-18_at_10.08.42_AM_xr4vun | Angelo M/O 290 in Grey Saint Laurent Marble | left\n\nHis designs have won numerous national and international awards, including the coveted German Red Dot Design Award, the German Design Award, the Good Design Award in Chicago and the AZ Award in Toronto. Represented by Ateliers Courbet in New York and Galerie Philia, Aerts'' work has been recognised by the Homo Faber Fellowship and featured at leading international design fairs. Neither Léo nor his designs are easy to categorise — the common thread is an unwavering commitment to characterful materials, structural honesty and the quiet ambition to create objects that outlast their era.' WHERE slug = 'leo-aerts-alinea';